{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_jordan_ver01/data/sn91068401/00332892782/1938021101/0280.xml":{"full_text":"ASSOCIATED PRESS AND CENTRAL PRESS\nCountry Club Members\nEndorse New Operation\nPlans For Coming Year\nTwo Memberships Offered to Citizens, One of $36 Per\nYear Includes All Privileges; sl2 Membership\nEmbraces All But Golf Seeking more Members\nAt the annual meeting of stockhold\ners and members of West End Coun\ntry Club, held at the chib house last\nnight with T. P. Ghol&on, president\npresiding, a new p\u2019.e.n of operation\nwas suggested and adopted by the\nbody that promises to .make the club\neven more active in years here\ntofore.\nThe new plans call for two member\nships, one embracing all privileges of\nthe club, including golf at $36 per\nyear, and the other embracing all pri\nvileges of the club with the exception\nof golf at sl2 per year.\nThere will he no charge for wives\nof husbands in good standing.\nFourteen directors were named, and\nthey will meet today to name officers\nof the club for the ensuing year, and\nto appoint the various committees.\nThe directors are J. T. Cheatham, R\nG. S. Davis, J. W. Jenkins, Rev. J. A.\nJones, O. T. Kirkland, R. G. Kittrell.\nM. F. Legg, C. O. Seifert, E. F. Shaw,\nN. P. Strausc, T. I. Gilliam, R. E. Cle\nments, D. L. Cannon and J. H. Brodie.\nThe new plan was discussed at\nlength at the well attended meeting,\nand was explained thusly: Ihe $36\nmemberships are intended for those\ninterested in golf as well as .having\nthe privilege of using the club for\nsocial purposes, ut least sl2 of such\nELECTRIFICATION\nTOUR FOR STUDY\nFive Rural Homes Will Be\nVisited by Group on\nNext Monday\nA tour of inspection of rural electri\nfication homes in Vance county will\nbe made by a group of farmers of the\ncounty on next Monday, County agent\nJ. W. Sanders announced today. Five\nrural homes equipped with nearly\nevery modern electric appliance for\nlightening the work of the farm will\nbe visited.\nD. E. Jones, rural electrification\nspecialist of N. C. State College, Ra\nleigh, is to be here and accompany the\nparty on the tour. He will explain\nhow the appliances already in use and\nmany others may be employed to the\ngreatest advantage and convenience.\nMr. Sanders said it was hoped many\nusers and prospective users of electri\ncity would find it possible to go along\nwith the party. Those whose homes\nwill be visited are inviting all who\nare interested to come to their homes.\nThe group will see motors for .pump\ning water, cutting wood, shredding\ncorn, chopping feed, churning, wash\ning and ironing, electric refrigerators,\nelectric ranges, percolators, radios and\nthe like.\nThe trip will be divided into morn\ning and afternoon visits. The first\naO O\nOEAUTY and Durability are two things you want to be sure\nof when you buy a new roof. The right roof improves the\nappearance of the entire building and gives protection from\nthe elements for many years.\nThere s such a variety of Bird Roofs in beautiful colors and\nblends that there is sure to be one just suited to your needs.\nThe sturdy construction and the uniform high quality of ma\nterials used in their manufacture assure you of many years of\nsatisfactory service.\nAlex S. Watkins\n\u201cWhere Quality Tells\nAnd Prices Sell.\u201d\ndues being required to help maintain\nthe overhead expenses and club ser\nvant hire incident to such social en\ntertainment, and the remaining $24 of\nthe vaa-\u2019s dues will go for golf course\nmaintenance and other expenses\nhereto.\nThe sl2 dues will he required for\noverhead and service expenses in\ncident only to social entertainment,\nand it was expressed that a sufficient\nnumber of citizens will join the club\nunder one of the memberships to en\na; lc the organization to offer free en\ntertainment for the members in addi\ntion to those arrangements provided\nby individuals or groups among club\nmembers on what is termed \u201cDutch\ntreat basis\u2019\u2019 for all expenses, except\nservice by club servants, lights, water,\nheat, and janitor service. It was point\ned out that dues cannot be kept so\nlow unless the membership is in\ncreased.\nAt present, the membership includes;\na v out 100, and it was the opinion of\nthose attending the session that Hen\nderson can have a country club with\n200 members.\nThe club\u2019s golf course will reach its.\ntop condition during the spring and\nsummer, and grass greens, recently\ninstalled, have had an opportunity to\nmature, and are in the best of play\ning condition during that period.\nhome to be visited is that of Mr. and\nMrs. Turner G. Stainback, at Cokes\nbury, at 10 a. m. At 11 a. m. the party\nwill go to the home of Mr. and Mrs.\nD. L. Hoyle, in the Cary\u2019s chapel sec\ntion. In the afternoon at 2 o\u2019clock\nthe home of Mr. and Mrs. H. B. New\nman. at Gillburg, will he visited, fol\nlowed by those of Mr. and Mrs. S. P.\nBrummitt and son and Mr. and Mrs.\nH. J. Parks, all like.wise in the Gill\nburg community.\nMr. Sanders and Mrs. Hattie F.\nPlummer, home demonstration agent,\nwill be with the party\nINTER MRS. STONE\nAT UNION CHAPEL\nHighly Respected Kittrell Township\nLady Laid to Rest in Church\nCemetery at 3 I*. M.\nFuneral services were conducted\nthis afternoon at 3 o\u2019clock from Union\nChapel M. P. church for Mrs. Sedia\nNash Stone, 74, well known lady of\nKittrell township, and interment was\nmade in the church cemetery at Union\nChapel.\nThere were many beautiful floral\ndesigns, attesting the high esteem in\nwhich Mrs. Stone was held by those\nwho knew her.\nActive pallbearers Melvin Ed\nwards, Clifton Edwards, L. W. Huff,\nJr., Pete Huff, T. A. Stone and B.\nF. Stone. Honorary pallbearers were.\nDr. J. H. Wheeler, W. S. Goodwyn, T.\nP. Stewart, Eddie Clayton, Ralph\nStone, N. F. Parham, Sam White, P.\nC. Smith, Brooks Brummitt, Russell\nBrummitt, J. W. Coghill, Charles Eld\nwards, Ed Young and Edwin Wells.\nHenderson Daily Dispatch\n$34,000 For\nSchool Gets\nBoard Okay\nCommissioners Ex\npected, In Turn, To\nApprove New Mid\ndleburg Project\nUnanimous approval of a $34,000\nbuilding project for Middleburg high\nschool was given by the Vance County\nBoard of Education at an adjourned\nmeeting Thursday afternoon, and the\nmatter now goes before the Vance\nBoard of County Commissioners for\napproval. As so_on as the commission\ners approve the project, possibly to\nmorrow, plans will be launched imme\ndiately for construction of the build\ning.\nThe board of education deferred ac\ntion on the Middleburg request at their\nmonthly meeting on Monday, and ad\njourned until Thursday for further\nconsideration. All members but one\nwere present for the meeting Thurs\nday.\nA delegation of Middleburg citizens\nhad appeared to urge the approval of\nthis work. Two officials of the State\nDepartment of Education, Dr. J. H.\nHighsmith, and C. G. Credle, inspect\ned the Middleburg property since Mon\nday and agreed with the education\nboard in its decision Monday, after a\nvisit to the school, that the work was\nneeded. Action had at first been de\nferred because of the cost, but the\noriginal figures was finally approved.\nThe new project will provide for\nnew class rooms, an enlargement of;\nthe auditorium, an office for the prin-'\ncipal and a library.\nIt is planned to call for bids and let*\nthe contract as quibkly as possible in\nexpectation of having the addition\nready for use at the opening of th\u00ae\nfall term of the school in September.\nUNEMPLOYMENT FUNDS\nARE BEING PUT OUT\nFirst of Checks Are .Received Here\nand Others Are Expected\nAlmost Daily\nUnemployment compensation funds\nfrhm State offices in Raleigh are al\nready being received here in small\nnumbers, but larger quantiteis of\nvouchers are looked for early next\nweek, it was learned today.\nSuch checks as have already teen\nreceived have been distributed to\nbeneficiaries. are being\nmade as fast as the checks arrive.\nFew, if any, checks resulting from\nshort time employment in the textile\nplpnts of'the city have been received,\nbut it was said these are expected the\nfirst or middle of next week.\nThe unemployment offices here, un\nder direction of George M. Suggs, has\nbeen busy for several weeks receiving,\napproving and forwarding applica\ntions for compensation to the State\noffices in Raleigh, presided over by*\nCharles M. Powell, chairman of the\nState Unemployment Compensation\nCommission.\nWith many persons out of work now\ndue to the business recession, the\nchecks are furnishing a cushion to\nward off at least a part of the suf\nfering and need occasioned by so\nmany persons being out of work.\nHEARING TONIGHT\nABOUT FIRE CHIEF\nA special meeting of the Henderson\nCity Council will be held this evening\nfor the purpose of hearing charges\nthat formed the basis of the suspen\nsion of Fire Chief E. T. Shepherd\nWednesday by Mayor Henry T.\nPowell.. The Council will either sus\ntain the suspension or order the chief\nreinstated. Mayor Powell has declined\nto state the charges in advance of j\nthe meeting. He said today that, so\nfar as he knew, the evidence in the\ncase would be brought out at an open\nmeeting of the Council.\nENGLISH STUDENTS\nVISIT DISPATCH\nTwo Groups of Mrs. J. Y. Paris\u2019\nJunior English class visited the Daily\nDispatch Wednesday and Thursday to\nlook over the plant in connection with\ntheir studies at this time, journalism.\nThe students visited all depart\nments of the paper, and spent most of\ntheir time in the composing room,\nwatching the actual making up of the\nday\u2019s jjaper.\nSHARP SLUMP SEEN\nIN REALTY MARKET\nA sharp slump in real estate ac\ntivity in Vance county in January was\nindicated in a compilation today of\nreal estate transfers as reflected in\ndeeds filed with the register of deedc\nduring the month. There were only\n36, as compared with 75 in January\nlast year, more than twice as much\nas last month. In December the total\nof deeds filed was 58.\n1820\u2014 Theodore O\u2019Hara, Kentucky\neditor, soldier and poet, author of\n\u201cThe Bivouac of the Dead,\u201d born at\nDanville, Ky. Died June 6, 1867.\n/^Speedt/^\\\n(headache)\nA- BeHerr A\nI DOES\nJITTERY-UPSET. |o\u00bb&2S*|\nRI ISyORK\n\nFormer Henderson Man,\nProminent Tobacconist,\nPasses Suddenly\nNews was received here late Thurs\nday by relatives and others of the\ndeath of Richard J. Wortham, retired\ntobacconist, formerly of this city, now\na resident of Knoxville, suburb of New\nYork City, and Asheville. Mr. Wor\ntham died in his sleep. He was about\n54.\nThe deceased was a native of Hen\nderson, and worked in warehouses\nand with large manufacturing com\npanies in the tobacco business here\nbefore going away to make a fortune\nin tolbacco. He spent more than a\nquarter of a century in Turkey and\nGreece with American tobacco inter\nests operating there. He returned to\nthi3 country several years ago and re\ntired, dividing his time between the\nhome at Knoxville, N. Y. and Ashe\nville, where the family also had a\nsummer home. Mr. Wortham is re\nlated to a number of prominent Hen\nderson people.\nMr. and Mrs. Wortham spent the\npast week-end here with Mr. and Mrs.\nJ. H. Brodie and left Monday for New\nYork. They had been to Asheville,\nwhere they visited and decorated on\nhis birthday anniversary the grave of\na son who was killed in an automobile\nwreck in the north about a year ago.\nHe was a student at Princeton, N. J.,.\nand was buried in Asheville.\n(Surviving are the widow, Mrs.\nNaomi Wortham, formerly of Ohio; a\ndaughter, Betty Ann Wortham; two\nbrothers, Willard of Jersey City, N.\nJ., and Alexander S. Wortham, of\nAsheville.\nFuneral services will be held in\nAsheville Saturday morning at Trin\nity church, with interment in River\nside cemetery there by the side of the\ndeceased son. Mr Wortham had\nnever become fully reconciled to the\nuntimely death of his boy, friends\nhere said.\nRelatives here include Mrs. C. L.\nCarter and Mrs. B. F. Harris, first\ncousins, and Turner Wortham a nep\nhew. Attending tne funeral will be\nMrs. T. R. Manning, an aunt, and Ned,\nReeves and William Manning, cou\nsins, all of Roanoke Rapids, and Mrs.\nHarris.\n\nWill Be In Parker Building,\non Garnett Street; Re\nmodeling) Begun\nRepairs and alterations have been\nstarted in changing the Parker build\ning on Garnett street for use of the\nA. P. Stores in its transformation\ninto a \u201csuper-store\u201d' of the chain\ngrocery. Alterations are being made\nby the Wi S. Parker estate, owner of\nthe property, and it is understood\nsome $3,000 will be (spent to convert\nthe building for its pew uses.\nIn addition to what the owners will\nspend, the grocery firm will spend\nconsiderable, it is understood, in set\nting up its own fixtures inside. A new\nand modern meat market is to be a\nfeature of the \u201csuper-store,\u201d it is un\nderstood.\nAbout a month is expected to be re\nquired to do all of the work neces\nsary and in making final preparations\nfor the opening of the establishment.\nThe front of the building is to be\nof dark-hued, highly polished glass to\ngive the new appearance of modernity\nThe building was the scene of the\nfirst store in the Rose chain here 23\nyears ago. It had since been cut into\ntwo store rooms and rented to vari\nous concerns at different times.\nGeorge\u2019s Case has been in one side of\nthe building for the past year or two.\nThe case has now moved after resist\ning custer proceedings last year, and\nwill be located several doors to the\nsouth on the same side of the street\nin a building that is now being re\nmodeled for the purpose.\nROAD TERmFgIVEN\nBY MAYOR POWELL\nTwo road terms were given two cf\nthe four defendants in city court o\nday before Mayor Homy T. Powell-\nJames Kelly wag g.altv of being\ndrunk, end -./as fine 1 $1 end costs.\nS. C. Ford, J\u2019., of Frank'.'nton. plead\ned\u2019 guilty to being drunk, and was\nfined $1 and costs of court.\nHezkiah Dowrev Negro, was con\nvicted of assaulting Richard Wood\nwith a deadly weapon, a brick, and\nwas given 90 days on the roads.\nJohn Thomas Burwell, Negro, drew\nan 18 months sentence on the impels\nfor breaking and entering end assault\ning Josephine Branch with a den cl. y\nweapon, a knife.\nCAN YOU ANSWER\nTHESE QUESTIONS?\nSee Page Four\n1. What is a moonshiner?\n2 Is hard-boiled properly a hyphenat\ned word.\n3. Which state is represented n C\u00b0 n\ngress by Senator Arthur Capper?\n4. What is the National Anthem of\n5. Name the only bachelor President\nof the U. S.\n6. Where is the Firth of Forth.\n7. What is the translation of the words\n\"Oroy Plata\u201d on the state seal of\nMontana?\n8. Who was nominated by the Presi\ndent to, fill the. vacany left by the\nretiring Justice of the Supreme\nCourt, George Sutherland?\n9. In which state is Moosehead Lake.\n10. Who was John Ruskin.\nEvery Effort Being Made\nTo Meet Relief Demands\nNo One Going To Be Allowed To Starve in Vance Coun\nty, Mrs. Austin Says; Mills Cooperating With County\nUndertaking To Meet Situation\nEverything possible is being done by\nthe county through the welfare de\npartment to alleviate the .suffering oc\ncasioned by the temporary closing of\na portion of the Henderson and Har\nriet Cotton Mills during the current\nbusiness \"recession,\u201d Mrs. E. R. Aus\ntin, welfare superintendent, said to\nday. Mrs. Austin said the county com\nmissioners had told her to see to it\nthat actual need was met, and they\nwould stand back of her as to the\ncost.\nNo one is going to be allowed to\nstarve in Vance county, and every one\nis going to be provided with the ab\nsolute essentials of a livelihood, Mrs.\nAustin emphatically stated in an in\nterview today. She said the officials of\nthe mills were giving their coopera\ntion in v work, and Mrs. Harry\nChavasse, welfare worker in the mill\ncommunities, and Miss Katherine Tea\ngue, of the mills\u2019 office staff, ary\nworking with the welfare department,\nin administering funds made avail\nable by the county. Moreover, the com\npanies are giving assistance in other\nways, it was explained.\nAt a special meeting held severa.\nweeks ago, the county commissioners\nassured Mrs. Austin that they would\nprovide the necessary funds to meet\nall absolute needs in the emergency.\nW. P. Parrish, member of the county\nboard, and an overseer in the Harriet\nv.\nRev. G. Van Stephens, of\nOxford, Makes Presenta\ntion at Meeting\nA medal for having the best ora\ntion in the twentieth district of the\nJunior Order was presented to Miss\nLucille Finch, daughter of Mr. and\nMrs. Clyde L. Finch, of Henderson\nat the weekly meeting of the local\ncouncil Thursday night. The meet\ning was presided over by S. N. Powell,\nbut during the opening pe\nriod from the secret session of the or\nder, J. F. White, of Oxford, district\ndeputy for the twentieth district, pre\ncided.\nRev. G. Van Stevens, Baptist min\nister of Oxford, made the presentation\nspeech, after which a few words were\nsaid also by Mr. and Mrs. Finch.\nA male quarette from Oxford gave\nseveral musical selections during the\nmeeting, accompanied at the piano by\nMrs. Raymond Weldon, of Henderson.\nMiss Finch had the best oration on\n\u201cAmericanism\u201d in the district. She\nwill enter an Eastern North Carolina\nelimination at Sanford on February\n25. The winner of that meet will be\nmatched against the winner in West\nern North Carolina at the annual\nState Council meeting of the Junio j\nOrder at Charlotte in August. The i\nStatewide award is a year\u2019s scholar\nship at Meredith College, of which the\npresident is Dr. Charles E. .Brewer,\nformer State and national councilor of\nthe Junior Order.\nAutomobile Fire \u2014Firemen were call\ned to an automobile fire on William 1\nstreet near Turner avenue last night\nabout 9:30 o\u2019clock. No damage was\nreported done to a car belonging to\nBill Kingsbury.\nmjffl\nV w VR .^gjo\nV _w>* l>i 1931 Ford sport coupe. 1932 Pontiac coupe, new\nW p Rumble seat, clean inside green finish, clean inside,\nand out, motor d* j| motor good, one of the H\nJ 1931 Ford Tudor New real good \u00abP 1 fiD best low priced d* A r\nblue finish, seat covers, 1936 Chevrolet standard cars we have fl*) ii\ntires good, extra clean and coach, original black fin- 1936 Chevrolet standard\none of the best model ish, upholstery good, mot- town sedan, new blue fin\n\u25a0A-\u2019s we (1 AC or one of d*JQ|* ish, tires new, motor extra\nhave had the best \u00abP*X\u00ab)D good, seat d\u00bbj J|-\n1931 Chevrolet sedan, new 1935 Chevrolet standard covers\nblack finish, seat covers, coach. Extra clean with 1934 Chevrolet Master se\ntires new, motor good, re- original black finish, tires dan, Deluxe model, knee\nmember the 31 model it new on rear, good on front action, motor good, uphol\nspeaks for $1 QC seat stery good, clean d*onr\nf\u00b0 r itself covers Vvvv inside and out I\nI SCOGGIN CHEVROLET CO. I\nB Warrenton, N. C. j\u00dfg\nFRIDAY, FEBRUARY 11, 1938\nmills, said the commissioners would\ngive every assistance possible.\nMrs. Austin explained that assis\ntance was not being given to persons\nworking on WPA projects nor to those\nreceiving unemployment compensa\ntion, but that aid was being extended\nto every one in actual need pending\nreceipt of the unemployment funds,\nand would continue to be until that\nmoney is received.\nThis program was outlined today\nfollowing a suggestion, made public\nthrough the Daily Dispatch Thursday\nof a citizen proposing that automo\nbile owners give the cost of one day\u2019s\noperation of their machines to meet\nthe emergency.\nWhen Borrowing\nIs Good Business!\nNo level-headed businessman\nborrows recklessly and this\nbank doesn\u2019t lend recklessly. But\nnearly all business successes\n\u2022have been built on the intelligent\nuse of borrowed money. And\nwhen businessmen of established\nreputation need working capital\nfor legitimate purposes and\nsound expansion, they find\nprompt and willing accommoda\ntion at this strong bank.\nFirst National\nIf\u00ae Bank\nHenderson,, N. C.\nMember Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation.\nB. H. PERRY SPEAKS\nBEFORE HI-Y CLUB\nProminent Attorney Addresses u; J\nSchool Boys at Meeting g\nThursday Evening\nB. H Perry, prominent Hcndera\nattorney, was the chief speaker JJ n\nweekly meeting of the Hi-Y club\nthe Henderson high school Thurs l\u00b0 f\nevening, talking on \u201cGood SportsmJ!?\u2019\nship in Athletics and in Life.\u201d n\nBobby Kittrell wa s in charge of n\nprogram, and the meeting -V as\nsided over by Billy Dennis, presirw\nof the club. In addition to hearing th\naddress by Mr. Perry, the club mart!\nplans for the remainder of <he sch 'i\nyear. All members of the club\npresent but two.\nKITTRELL TO TALK\nFOR BIBLE CLASS\nR. G. Kittrell will teach the O\u2019Kellv\nBible class of the First Congregation\nal Christian Church Sunday morning\nat the Sunday school hour, it un\nstated today.\nAll members were urged to h e pre\nsent, and visitors are cordially wel\ncome to hear Mr. Kittrell.","height":"28191","width":"21231"}}
